<paragraph id="8B8118792F53FFE902E2FC62E1252DB1" blockId="62.[189,303,979,1005]" box="[189,303,979,1005]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<heading id="D0C9AF152F53FFE902E2FC62E1252DB1" bold="true" box="[189,303,979,1005]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B94AC46B2F53FFE902E2FC62E1252DB1" bold="true" box="[189,303,979,1005]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8118792F53FFE902E2FBB2E5172A3E" blockId="62.[189,1399,1026,1123]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicName id="4C3E63FA2F53FFE902E2FBB2E1AF2A40" box="[189,421,1027,1052]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="megaptera">
<emphasis id="B94AC46B2F53FFE902E2FBB2E1AF2A40" box="[189,421,1027,1052]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Begonia megaptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E63FA2F53FFE90081FBB2E36A2A40" authorityName="D. Don (Don" authorityYear="1825" box="[734,864,1026,1052]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="palmata">
<emphasis id="B94AC46B2F53FFE90081FBB2E36A2A40" box="[734,864,1026,1052]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">B. palmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can instantly be distinguished as it lacks the reddish brown silky indumentum. The rather poorly known 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E63FA2F53FFE901F2FB97E44A2A63" box="[941,1088,1061,1087]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="beddomei">
<emphasis id="B94AC46B2F53FFE901F2FB97E44A2A63" box="[941,1088,1061,1087]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">B. beddomei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has similar scalloped leaves, but has female flowers with 8 tepals and hairs on the petioles and leaf lamina underside.
</paragraph>
